[[Air Chief Marshal]] '''Sir Gareth Thomas Butler Clayton''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KCB|DFC}} & [[Medal bar|Bar]] (13 November 1914 – 5 February 1992) was a senior [[Royal Air Force]] officer who served as [[Air Secretary]] from 1970 to 1972.

==RAF career==
Clayton joined the Royal Air Force in 1936.<ref name=air>[http://www.rafweb.org/Biographies/Clayton.htm Air of Authority – A History of RAF Organisation – Air Marshal Sir Gareth Clayton]</ref> He served in [[World War II]] as a Flight Commander with [[No. 25 Squadron RAF|No. 25 Squadron]] and then with [[No. 100 Squadron RAF|No. 100 Squadron]] before being appointed Officer Commanding [[No. 576 Squadron RAF|No. 576 Squadron]] in 1943 and then Deputy Station Commander at [[RAF Faldingworth]] in 1944.<ref name=air/> He then served on the Air Staff at [[No. 1 Group RAF|No. 1 Group]] and as a Staff Officer on the Future Operational Plans Staff at the [[Air Ministry]].<ref name=air/>

After the War he became Air Attaché in [[Lisbon]] and then Station Commander first at [[RAF Cottesmore]] and then at [[RAF Honington]].<ref name=air/> He was appointed Director of Operations – Air Transport & Overseas Theatres in 1959, Air Officer Commanding [[No. 11 Group RAF|No. 11 Group]] in 1962 and Chief  of Staff for the [[Second Tactical Air Force]] in 1963.<ref name=air/> He went on to be Director-General of RAF Personnel Services in 1966, Chief of Staff at Headquarters [[RAF Strike Command]] in 1969<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=45051|supp=yes|startpage=2556|date=3 March 1970|accessdate=2011-03-26}}</ref> and [[Air Secretary]] in 1970 before retiring in 1972.<ref name=air/>

